<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Luke Bonell (CYS0074)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">Written evidence </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> Luke Bonell </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">CYS0074)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">1. My experience is limited to London so these points can only relate to here.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">2. Travel by </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">bicycle will become safer the more people do it.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">3. The way to increase cycle participation is not to emphasise how dangerous it is, having the police stop cyclists and tell them they should wear helmets and high vis jackets is counter productive.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">4. The s</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">afest cycling cities are ones where cycling is normal, all drivers know someone who rides, and there is no them and us culture.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">5. Although segregated cycle lanes are great (they have to be wide enough for at least two riders next to each other) they are n</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ot the only way- with a four lane road like the strand it would be much more cycling friendly if for example the left two lane were reserved for buses and cyclist going both ways, and the right two lane for cars (this works because there is a central barri</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">er)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">6. Cyclists need at least equal representation within official TFL groups as other interest parties such as taxis, otherwise vested interests will stop such relatively cheap and easy fixes being implemented.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">7. Cycle super high ways are useless if cars</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> are allowed to park in them, or if there is not enough road space so buses have to block them.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">8. Contraflows designed to ease traffic flow are extremely bad for cyclists, as they usually are blocked with stationary traffic that uses all the available spa</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">ce, forcing the rider to weave in and out.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">9. Bus drivers are among the most aggressive toward cyclists. It should be made easier to identify specific drivers (maybe a how am I driving style number on the back) and a complaints procedure put in place with </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">a three strikes and out policy.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">10. The most important step is to give cycling groups a voice in road design, at least proportional to the amount of journeys made by bike (or the amount of journeys you would like to see made by bike)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">11. In a perfect world</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt"> the cycling proficiency test would be a required module in the standard driving test.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>